        "#Timsort\n",
        "\n",
        "###this document will explain the running time of Timsort algorithm\n",
        "<p>Timsort is a hybrid sorting algorithm. It is used to give optimal results while dealing with real-world data.<p>\n",
        "\n",
        "in a very simplified way this i show it works:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. The array is broken down into runs (minruns) preferably, using (n/minrun) as a power of 2, thus merge sort gives optimal results in that case\n",
        "\n",
        "2. Initialize the size of the run as 32 or 64.\n",
        "\n",
        "3. Sort every run using insertion sort. If the array size is smaller than 64, then it is just sorted using insertion sort.\n",
        "\n",
        "4. Merge all the runs one by one using merge sort.\n",
        "\n",
        "5. After every iteration, double the size of the merged sub-array.![timsort.png](data:image/png;base64,)"

        "##run length\n",
        "<p>The exact way that the run lengths are determined isnt important. Whats important is the details of what the run length is.\n",
        "\n",
        "Insertion sort is most efficient on short collections, so we want our run length to be relatively small. At the same time, the merging algorithm works best when the number of runs is a power of two or slightly less than one. We also want to minimize our number of runs, preferring slightly longer runs over more of them, as long as they dont get too long.\n",
        "\n",
        "One such algorithm for this involves starting with the entire array length and halving it until we get below a certain threshold. By halving it each time, we guarantee that well have a power of two for the number of runs. Equally, our threshold will mean that we keep the number of runs down to a minimum that is still efficient enough for the insertion sort portion<p>"
      ],

        "##mergin runs\n",
        "<p>Once we have a collection of runs that are internally sorted, we can begin to merge them together. This uses the merging algorithm that merge sort uses, but because the runs are already sorted, we only need the merging part.\n",
        "\n",
        "We start out by merging adjacent runs together. After this, well have effectively got sorted runs that are twice the length of before. We can keep recursively merging these growing runs together until weve merged the entire collection.\n",
        "\n",
        "The merging of two runs together works by iterating over both runs at the same time and, at each step, selecting the lowest element from the two. When we reach the end of one of the runs, we can select everything remaining from the other run  since we know that they must all be greater than the last selected element<p>"

        "# running time\n",
        "<p>because this algorithm uses insertion we need to know it's running time fist, as said before we are examinating Tim sort i'm not overextending on that one, is knwon it's running time in O() notation is n^2 in worst case <p>\n",
        "<p>intuitively, since binary insertion sort is only employed when it is not harmful to the performance, the worst case of Tim sort would be analogus to that of merge sort which is n(log(n))<p>\n",
        "\n",
        "\n"
